definition.p:
Suppose that $\vect{u},\,\vect{v}\in\complex{m}$.  Then $\vect{u}$ and $\vect{v}$ are equal, written $\vect{u}=\vect{v}$ if

\vectorentry{\vect{u}}{i}&=\vectorentry{\vect{v}}{i}
&&1\leq i\leq m

Suppose that $\vect{u},\,\vect{v}\in\complex{m}$. The sum of $\vect{u}$ and $\vect{v}$ is the vector $\vect{u}+\vect{v}$ defined by

\vectorentry{\vect{u}+\vect{v}}{i}
&=\vectorentry{\vect{u}}{i}+\vectorentry{\vect{v}}{i}
&&1\leq i\leq m

Suppose $\vect{u}\in\complex{m}$ and $\alpha\in\complex{\null}$, then the scalar multiple of $\vect{u}$ by $\alpha$ is the vector $\alpha\vect{u}$ defined by

\vectorentry{\alpha\vect{u}}{i}
&=\alpha\vectorentry{\vect{u}}{i}
&&1\leq i\leq m

subsection.p:
Be careful with the notion of the vector $\vect{-u}$.  This is a vector that we add to $\vect{u}$ so that the result is the particular vector $\zerovector$.  This is basically a property of vector addition.  It happens that we can compute $\vect{-u}$ using the other operation, scalar multiplication.  We can prove this directly by writing that

\vectorentry{\vect{-u}}{i}
=-\vectorentry{\vect{u}}{i}
=(-1)\vectorentry{\vect{u}}{i}
=\vectorentry{(-1)\vect{u}}{i}

We will see later how to derive this property as a consequence of several of the ten properties listed in .

exercise.solution:
Performing the indicated operations (, ), we obtain the vector equations

\colvector{11\\6\\17}
&= 3\colvector{1\\2\\-1} + 4\colvector{2 \\ 0 \\ x}
= \colvector{11\\6\\ -3 + 4x}

Since the entries of the vectors must be equal by , we have $-3 + 4x = 17$, which leads to $x = 5$.

exercise.problem:
Solve the given vector equation for $\alpha$, or explain why no solution exists:

\alpha\colvector{1\\2\\-1}+
4\colvector{3\\4\\2}
=
\colvector{-1\\0\\4}

exercise.solution:
Performing the indicated operations (, ), we obtain the vector equations

\colvector{\alpha \\ 2\alpha\\ -\alpha} + \colvector{12\\16\\8}
&=\colvector{\alpha + 12 \\ 2\alpha + 16\\ -\alpha + 8}
=\colvector{-1\\0\\4}

Thus, if a solution $\alpha$ exists, by  then $\alpha$ must satisfy the three equations:

\alpha + 12 &= -1\\
2\alpha + 16 &= 0\\
-\alpha + 8 &= 4

which leads to $\alpha = -13$, $\alpha = -8$ and $\alpha = 4$.
Since $\alpha$ cannot simultaneously have three different values, there is no solution to the original vector equation.

exercise.problem:
Solve the given vector equation for $\alpha$, or explain why no solution exists:

\alpha\colvector{3\\2\\-2}+
\colvector{6\\1\\2}
=
\colvector{0\\-3\\6}

exercise.solution:
Performing the indicated operations (, ), we obtain the vector equations

\colvector{3\alpha \\ 2\alpha\\ - 2\alpha} + \colvector{6\\1\\2}
&= \colvector{3\alpha + 6 \\ 2\alpha + 1\\ -2\alpha + 2}
 = \colvector{0\\-3\\6}

Thus, if a solution $\alpha$ exists, by  then $\alpha$ must satisfy the three equations:

3\alpha + 6 &= 0\\
2\alpha + 1 &= -3\\
-2 \alpha + 2 &= 6

which leads to $3\alpha = -6$, $2\alpha = -4$ and $-2\alpha = 4$.
And thus, the solution to the given vector equation is $\alpha = -2$.

exercise.problem:
Find $\alpha$ and $\beta$ that solve the vector equation.

\alpha\colvector{1\\0}+
\beta\colvector{0\\1}
=
\colvector{3\\2}

exercise.solution:
Performing the indicated operations (, ), we obtain the vector equations

\colvector{3\\2}
&=\alpha\colvector{1\\0} + \beta\colvector{0\\1}
=\colvector{\alpha + 0 \\ 0 + \beta}
=\colvector{\alpha\\ \beta}

Since the entries of the vectors must be equal by , we have $\alpha = 3$ and $\beta = 2$.

exercise.problem:
Find $\alpha$ and $\beta$ that solve the vector equation.

\alpha\colvector{2\\1}+
\beta\colvector{1\\3
}=
\colvector{5\\0}

exercise.solution:
Performing the indicated operations (, ), we obtain the vector equations

\colvector{5\\0}
&= \alpha\colvector{2\\1} + \beta\colvector{1\\3}
= \colvector{2\alpha + \beta \\ \alpha + 3\beta}

Since the entries of the vectors must be equal by , we obtain the system of equations

2\alpha + \beta &= 5\\
\alpha + 3\beta &= 0.

which we can solve by row-reducing the augmented matrix of the system,

\begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1 & 5\\
1 & 3 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
&\rref
\begin{bmatrix}
\leading{1} & 0 & 3\\
0 & \leading{1} & -1
\end{bmatrix}

Thus, the only solution is $\alpha = 3$, $\beta = -1$.

For all $1\leq i\leq m$,

\vectorentry{\vect{u}+\vect{v}}{i}
&=\vectorentry{\vect{u}}{i}+\vectorentry{\vect{v}}{i}
&&\text{}\\
&=\vectorentry{\vect{v}}{i}+\vectorentry{\vect{u}}{i}
&&\text{Commutativity in $\complex{\null}$}\\
&=\vectorentry{\vect{v}+\vect{u}}{i}
&&\text{}

With equality of each component of the vectors $\vect{u}+\vect{v}$ and $\vect{v}+\vect{u}$ being equal  tells us the two vectors are equal.
